---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base path="/">
  <div class="wrap">
    <img class="portrait" src="/img/me/headshot.png" alt="Gabriel Berger" width="210" height="252" />
    <h1>Gabriel Berger</h1>

    <p class="lede">
      I'm an undergraduate at Stanford studying math, computer science, and statistics.
      Most of what I do is low-level systems work: this past spring I built a RISC-V CPU
      that runs compiled C, and before that a WiFi driver from scratch.
    </p>

    <p>
      I also write code for research labs. At UCSF I rebuilt a sequencing
      pipeline for leukemia research, and this summer I'm at the
      <a href="/research">Stanford Cancer Institute</a> working on a way to spot a hard-to-find
      cancer from a blood draw.
    </p>

    <ul class="links">
      <li><a href="mailto:gberger@stanford.edu">email <span class="arrow">↗</span></a></li>
      <li><a href="https://github.com/gjberger">github <span class="arrow">↗</span></a></li>
      <li><a href="https://www.linkedin.com/in/gabriel-berger-69968a336/">linkedin <span class="arrow">↗</span></a></li>
      <li><a href="/resume">résumé <span class="arrow">→</span></a></li>
    </ul>

    <h2>currently</h2>

    <!-- Powerset email gabriel@powerset.co is STAGED — swap the reach-out link to it once forwarding to Gmail is wired. -->
    <div class="entry">
      <div class="head">
        <h3>Powerset</h3>
        <span class="when">2026</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Stanford lead and a software engineer (consultant) at Powerset, an
        early-stage talent firm that invests in young builders. I build the
        software and data tooling to find them, and run the firm's Stanford
        presence. If you're building something, I'd like to hear about it.
        <a href="mailto:gberger@stanford.edu">Reach out.</a>
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="entry">
      <div class="head">
        <h3>Sequencing pipeline at UCSF</h3>
        <span class="when">since 2025</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Rebuilding DAB-seq v2, a C++17 pipeline that turns raw FASTQ reads into
        per-cell genotypes and antibody-marker profiles for leukemia research. It
        runs about 10× faster than before.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="entry">
      <div class="head">
        <h3>Liquid-biopsy research at the Stanford Cancer Institute</h3>
        <span class="when">summer 2026</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        Comparing cell-free DNA and RNA to tell Richter transformation apart from
        the leukemia it comes from. The goal is to catch an aggressive,
        hard-to-biopsy cancer from a blood draw.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="entry">
      <div class="head">
        <h3>Systems projects</h3>
        <span class="when">ongoing</span>
      </div>
      <p>
        A RISC-V CPU, a bare-metal WiFi driver, an e-ink dashboard. More on the
        <a href="/projects">projects</a> page.
      </p>
    </div>

    <h2>elsewhere</h2>
    <p>
      I'm also a musician: I play alto saxophone, and came up through the SFJAZZ mentee
      program, lessons with Dann Zinn, and the studio band and combos at CJC under Dave
      Eshelman and Colin Hogan, among other things. I also sit silent vipassana meditation, keep picking up
      languages (Japanese, Spanish, Hebrew), and read more than I probably should.
    </p>

    <aside class="give-note">
      <span class="mark">&#9829;</span> I give blood regularly, at
      <a href="https://stanfordbloodcenter.org/">Stanford Blood Center</a> and
      <a href="https://www.vitalant.org/">Vitalant</a>, and in 2026 I organized a
      drive in memory of my mom, who I lost to leukemia. One donation can save up
      to three lives. If you're eligible,
      <a href="https://www.vitalant.org/">find a drive</a> or
      <a href="https://stanfordbloodcenter.org/">book at Stanford</a>. It's one of
      the easiest meaningful things you can do.
    </aside>
  </div>
</Base>
